		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/poster2</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> poster:</span><br><i>Towards Controlling Refinements of Statecharts</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ConnerHansen.html">Conner Hansen</a>, <a href="../profile/EugeneSyriani.html">Eugene Syriani</a>, <a href="../profile/LeviLúcio.html">Levi Lúcio</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1503.07266">10.48550/arXiv.1503.07266</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s core problem is controlling incremental refinement across versions of a Statecharts model to support predictable evolution and maintenance.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It defines a formal refinement relation and constraints (e.g., inclusion conditions over events/guards/structure) to guarantee behaviour preservation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> “Refinement” is treated as a disciplined stepwise development relation (additive, structure-preserving), i.e., a vertical refinement discipline over models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> Statecharts are treated as a domain-specific modeling language whose refinement rules constrain how models can be extended.</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
